It remains to notice certain clauses which were sometimes inserted in the formula at the instance οἱ the defendant, viz. exceptiones and praescriptiones pro τεο. It was a peculiar rule of the formulary system that the defendant was not allowed to plead some grounds of defence in iudicio unless they had been alleged in iure, and the judge’s attention expressly called to them by an addition to the formula. Exceptiones are pleas of this character: defences which do not actually traverse the allegation of the plaintiff, but set up a countervailing right, rendering the former of at least no present value, and which, if they are to be successfully pleaded, require (though to a larger extent in some classes of actions than in others) to be tersely embodied in the formula, by an addition to the Intenti0, instructing the iudex to condemn the defendant only on the fulfilment of two conditions instead, as usual, of one, viz.
